<HEADLINE>
<P>
BOOK REVIEWS; 
</P>
<P>
MAMET STEPS DOWN FROM SHRINE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICHARD EDER, TIMES BOOK CRITIC 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some Freaks by David Mamet (Viking: $16.95; 182 pages). 
</P>
<P>
Admire David Mamet and you'll get your head bitten off, or at the very least, a 
cigar in the face. 
</P>
<P>
There he is on the book jacket, glowering from his car window, half his face in 
shadow. If you are a cop who'd stopped him for a broken tail-light, you'd 
return to the cruiser and radio for back-up. If you are his wife, you'd take 
the garbage out yourself, and make sure not to walk between him and the TV set. 
</P>
<P>
Such, more or less, is the image suggested in this assorted collection of 
articles, addresses, musings and rumbles. Mamet is virtually a poet of the 
theater, drawing a musical sweet haplessness out of his sharpies and dummies. 
He doesn't thank you to say so. 
</P>
<P>
"I am a card-carrying member of the ACLU and the NRA and I never signed up to 
be sensitive," he writes in a piece about playing poker with the boys. 
</P>
<P>
Attending a convention of counterinsurgency groupies sponsored by Soldier of 
Fortune magazine, he frets that his Oxford shirt and blue jeans will mark him 
as "another wussy Eastern intellectual with a marvelous gift for dialogue." 
</P>
<P>
He takes part wholeheartedly, shooting off a pistol and entering the pugil 
stick contest. He knocks his first opponent into the swimming pool, and is 
knocked over by the second, though not before overpowering him in the 
preliminary ritual scream. 
</P>
<P>
"Lovely people," he writes of the conventioneers, even if he doesn't agree with 
some of their ideas. "But then I don't agree with some of my own ideas and seem 
powerless to rid myself of them." And he adds that they "seemed to love the 
idea of America in much the same way that someone else might love the idea of 
the Theater -- that is, as a perfect institution." 
</P>
<P>
By rights, that last half-phrase would qualify as sensitive, and maybe 
brilliant. But Mamet, one of our authentic theater artists, may have made his 
bed but he will not be caught dead lying in it. In these assorted pieces, he 
hacks away at any hint of enshrinement. 
</P>
<P>
He tells the Signet Society at Harvard -- he must have jumped at the chance to 
perform the lion in a den of sensitive Daniels -- that if he became an artist 
it was not mainly because of talent or message. Perhaps it was "to accommodate 
and embrace a deviant personality which was not going to be employed 
elsewhere." If you're a left-handed plumber, in other words, you do left-handed 
pipe-bends. 
</P>
<P>
It can be as tedious for an artist to flaunt his hairy chest as his hair shirt. 
Mamet's art, in any case, does not principally lie in writing such occasional 
pieces as are collected here in "Some Freaks." Many are as rough in workmanship 
as in message; there is a lot of sounding off and putting the feet up. It makes 
the feet feel good, but readers aren't feet. 
</P>
<P>
Aside from eight or nine pieces too slight or ephemeral to survive collecting, 
Mamet usually has something worthwhile, or arresting, or bruising to say. He is 
witty and idiosyncratic for part of the trip. The trick is to get off in time. 
The stop after idiosyncrasy is sententiousness. 
</P>
<P>
Mamet's notes on being a first-time film director -- "House of Games" -- nicely 
distinguish those things a director can do from those he should submit to. 
Sometimes, a general's job is simply to be seen on his white horse. Mamet 
writes of stepping ceremonially up to the viewfinder for each shot -- at this 
stage, the real responsibility belongs to the cinematographer -- and 
ostentatiously reversing the bill on his cap. 
</P>
<P>
Discussing acting for TV, he advises the performer to do little. The script 
will furnish the characterization, he writes. Acting technique should aim "to 
render the actor sufficiently uninflected to allow the audience to accept him 
in a multiplicity of roles." 
</P>
<P>
Two of the pieces denounce what Mamet sees as the tendency of American Jews to 
downplay their Jewishness. Reform Judaism, in particular, he calls "religion in 
a plain brown wrapper, the selling point of which was that it would not 
embarrass us." 
</P>
<P>
He argues that American Jews are dedicated to speaking up for civil rights and 
social equality for all minority groups except their own. Young Jewish women of 
his generation, he writes, flocked to enroll in Black Studies programs. And 
their friends and families, he adds, "supported them in their support of Black 
self-love at the same time we supported them in surgically recarving their 
faces so that they would look less 'Jewish.' " 
</P>
<P>
There is a brutal wit here -- it sounds like Jackie Mason -- but it seems a 
partial view, to say the least, and considering the backlash among Jewish 
voters to the Rev. Jesse Jackson, partly outdated. 
</P>
<P>
It is also hard to know what he means when he laments that Jewish houses look 
like Yankee houses and have no visual identity. What would a specifically 
Jewish house look like? What, for that matter, would a specifically Catholic 
house look like? If you want to be fundamental about it: like tents, both of 
them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Book Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA121489-0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 148182 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
December 14, 1989, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
View; Part E; Page 13; Column 1; View Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
374 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MISS MANNERS: A REASON FOR REVENGE? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JUDITH MARTIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DEAR MISS MANNERS -- For several months I wooed an attractive young lady. I had 
not won her, however (nor had we had one of those annoying, awkward, modern 
"little talks"), when I began to sense a distinct chill. After a few 
inconclusive weeks, I reluctantly decided to stop calling her. Unfortunately, 
but not surprisingly, she stopped calling me as well. 
</P>
<P>
Within a week, both intuition and hard evidence began piling up, revealing that 
she was making a serious play for my brand-new roommate. He seems quite 
receptive, too. 
</P>
<P>
I run into her about once a week, and I have to live with him. I'm pretending 
nothing has happened, but this is unsatisfactory. What would be a more 
appropriate response -- a fit of outraged bellowing or some more devious 
revenge? 
</P>
<P>
GENTLE READER -- Miss Manners regrets to inform you that you are responding 
correctly. That knowledge should gratify you, but she realizes that it would be 
infinitely more satisfactory if she told you to rig paper bags full of water to 
fall over them on the sofa, and to write nasty remarks about them on the 
neighborhood walls. 
</P>
<P>
The fact is that one does not retain an option on former romantic partners. 
Unpleasant as it is to see another more favored than you, and at close hand, 
nothing they have done merits your being unpleasant. Pretending you don't care 
is the only polite stance. 
</P>
<P>
This does not preclude dignified revenge. Most love affairs come to an end if 
you wait long enough, and there may be some satisfaction for you in observing 
this. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR MISS MANNERS -- What do you say to people who tell you what they want you 
to get them for Christmas, when you have no intention of getting them anything? 
</P>
<P>
My sister-in-law has been doing this. My husband and his sister have never 
exchanged gifts for any occasion. Suddenly this year she has started telling me 
things like, "You could get me this or that for Christmas -- I know y'all can 
afford it." 
</P>
<P>
GENTLE READER -- Your sister-in-law wants to change that policy, but perhaps 
you had better make sure she isn't thinking of just changing half of it. 
</P>
<P>
You could say "Oh, do you think we should start exchanging presents?" or "You 
know, we've never exchanged presents, so you ought to be telling that to Santa 
Claus, not me." 
</P>
</TEXT>
