<HEADLINE>
<P>
DR. JOYCE BROTHERS: POSSIBLE TO HEAR DURING SURGERY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. JOYCE BROTHERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DEAR DR. BROTHERS: Recently, I underwent surgery in our local hospital, and 
later I told my husband that I recalled the doctors and anesthesiologists 
discussing the scores of a ballgame while I was under the knife. My husband, 
who is a doctor, laughed at this and told me I couldn't possibly remember 
anything. Could I have just imagined this? -- C.J. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR C.J.: Of course it's possible that you may have imagined it, or you may 
have heard this conversation before you were fully anesthetized. It's also 
possible, however, that some part of your brain recorded such a conversation. 
</P>
<P>
New studies have given credence to the idea that patients who are completely 
anesthetized can still register some of what goes on around them. This is 
significant information because it indicates that patients may comprehend 
enough of what is said during surgery to affect the course of their recovery. 
They may respond to positive comments and negative comments may upset patients 
long after surgery. 
</P>
<P>
The ability of patients to learn under anesthetic was revealed in a study by 
researchers at Cambridge University where patients were given information about 
a number of odd facts and later when questioned on the topics scored 
significantly higher than would be expected. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR DR. BROTHERS: My 22-year-old daughter has an annoying, alarming habit of 
buying out department stores. We're not poor, but if she continues to use her 
credit cards with such abandon, we soon will be. What really irritates me is 
that she buys things she doesn't need or use. My late wife told me about the 
joys of buying, but why buy what you don't need? I've talked with my daughter 
about this. She agrees with me, but she doesn't change. What's wrong? -- P.W. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR P.W.: Some people use shopping as a way to escape from their problems. If 
they're depressed, they rush to a department store and buy a new dress, new 
shoes or new coat. Such purchases are usually unrelated to need -- at least, 
not the need of clothing. They are closely related to emotional needs. This 
kind of misuse of shopping is dangerous because this can quickly develop into 
an addiction. 
</P>
<P>
Buying something -- anything -- becomes a quick fix in much the same way a shot 
of drugs is a fix for a junkie, or placing a bet relieves anxiety for a 
compulsive gambler. Whether the addiction is to food, drugs, alcohol or 
shopping, the relief it gives is only temporary and does nothing to solve the 
real problem. 
</P>
<P>
Addicts typically suffer from loneliness, a feeling of emptiness and a low 
sense of self-esteem. I suspect that your daughter would profit from some 
professional counseling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA121489-0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 148192 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
December 14, 1989, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
