<HEADLINE>
<P>
BACK TO BASICS: TO MASH, RICE OR WHIP -- PONDERING THE OPTIONS OF POTATO 
PREPARATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOAN DRAKE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When it comes to mashed potatoes, there is little consensus about what is 
correct or incorrect. The answers to such questions as what is the best utensil 
to use for mashing the spuds and whether they should or shouldn't have lumps 
are strictly a matter of personal preference. 
</P>
<P>
What does make a difference, however, is the variety used for mashing. Of the 
two basic types of potatoes -- waxy and nonwaxy -- the latter are best suited 
for this procedure because of their low sugar and high starch content. 
</P>
<P>
If placed in a solution of one of pound salt in one gallon of water, waxy 
potatoes will float, while more dense nonwaxy potatoes will sink to the bottom. 
Unfortunately, this is not a very practical test to conduct while shopping at 
the supermarket, so generally speaking, rely on the thick-skinned potatoes such 
as russets to be nonwaxy. 
</P>
<P>
Select potatoes that are firm, free from large cuts, growth cracks and 
sprouting eyes. Avoid any with green tinged skins. 
</P>
<P>
According to "The Whole Potato Catalog," a publication of the Potato Board, 
potatoes to be mashed may be either boiled or steamed: 
</P>
<P>
"To Boil: In a heavy saucepan with tight-fitting lid, cook potatoes in about 
one inch of boiling, salted water until fork-tender. Whole, 30 to 40 minutes; 
cut-up, 20 to 25 minutes. (If lid doesn't fit tightly, water may boil away so 
check occasionally and add more water if necessary.) 
</P>
<P>
"To Steam: Place wire rack on bottom of a kettle or large saucepan and add 
water to just below the level of the rack. Bring the water to a boil, add 
potatoes and cook, tightly covered, until fork-tender. Whole, 30 to 45 minutes; 
cut-up, 20 to 30 minutes. (Check occasionally to see if water should be added, 
if lid is not tight fitting.)" 
</P>
<P>
Most people prefer to peel potatoes before cooking, however this step can be 
done afterwards, or when using a ricer may be eliminated to save time. During 
boiling, pieces of nonwaxy varieties tend to slough off and the potatoes lose 
their shape. Once cooked, boiled potatoes should be drained well before 
mashing. 
</P>
<P>
Milk, evaporated milk, half and half or cream may be used when mashing 
potatoes. Whatever the choice, it should be heated; adding cold liquid cools 
the potatoes and tends to make them gummy. 
</P>
<P>
The more liquid used, the more creamy and thinner the end product. The amount 
needed also varies depending on the potatoes -- soil, climate and fertilizer 
used during growth all have their effects. Softened butter or margarine, salt 
and pepper are optional additions. 
</P>
<P>
Use a potato masher, electric mixer or ricer to mash the potatoes. Following 
are techniques for using each device. 
</P>
<P>
POTATO MASHER: Press the tool into the potatoes in a downward motion, forcing 
them through the cutting grid. Gradually add milk, butter and salt and pepper 
to taste, beating with the potato masher, fork or wire whisk until light and 
fluffy. 
</P>
<P>
ELECTRIC MIXER: Begin by mashing the potatoes slightly with the stationary 
beaters. Turn the mixer on low speed and whip to the desired consistency, 
gradually adding milk, butter and salt and pepper to taste. 
</P>
<P>
RICER: Place the boiled potatoes in the perforated cylinder, then squeeze the 
long handles together to force the contents through the ricer holes. Let the 
rice-like pieces mound in the serving dish. Gradually add milk, butter and salt 
and pepper to taste and beat the potatoes with a fork, spoon or wire whisk 
until light and fluffy. 
</P>
<P>
Most sources agree that mashed potatoes are best served immediately. If they 
must be held, spoon into a buttered casserole and smooth a light film of cream 
over the top. Keep warm in an oven heated to 250 degrees. 
</P>
<P>
Another technique is to set the pan of finished potatoes in a larger one of hot 
water. Cover with a towel to absorb the steam. 
</P>
<P>
 Suggestions for column topics may be sent to Back to Basics, Food Section, The 
Times, Times Mirror Square, Los Angeles 90053. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, There's little consensus about the correct way to mash potatoes. Left to 
right, a potato masher, electric mixer or ricer may all be used to prepare this 
vegetable, depending on personal preference. MARSHA TRAEGER / Los Angeles 
Times; Photo, With a potato mashing tool, press the peeled and cooked tubers in 
a downward motion, forcing the pulp up through the cutting grid. ; Photo, Using 
an electric mixer, mash the potatoes slightly with the stationary beaters, then 
turn on low speed and beat to the desired consistency. ; Photo, When using a 
ricer, place the boiled potatoes in the cylinder and squeeze the handles so 
rice-like pieces are forced through the holes. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
