<HEADLINE>
<P>
GRAY TO PAY $5,000, SIT OUT A GAME; 3 LAKERS ALSO FINED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SAM McMANIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MIAMI 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Byron Scott and Michael Cooper, who said that they had engaged in Tuesday 
night's fight with Charlotte Hornet center Stuart Gray strictly to protect 
Laker teammate James Worthy, nonetheless were fined by the NBA office 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
Scott was fined $2,000 and Cooper $1,000 for "adding to the escalation of the 
altercation," according to Rod Thorn, the NBA's vice president of operations. 
Gray was fined $5,000 and suspended for a game for fighting with no fewer than 
five Lakers. Worthy was fined $500 for pushing Gray. 
</P>
<P>
Laker players were told of the fines before Wednesday night's game against the 
Miami Heat. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm going to pay it," said Scott, who also was fined $500 after being the 
third player in a pushing incident between Magic Johnson and Phoenix's Kevin 
Johnson on Nov. 7. 
</P>
<P>
Said Cooper: "I guess it's justified. There's nothing we can do about it. (The 
league) has made a stand about fighting." 
</P>
<P>
Added Worthy: "It's justice." 
</P>
<P>
Gray, according to Thorn, was fined and suspended for "initiating an 
altercation with James Worthy, throwing a punch and brawling." He will sit out 
Charlotte's game tonight at Washington. SAM McMANIS 
</P>
</TEXT>
