<HEADLINE>
<P>
PREP FOOTBALL ALL-STARS 1989; 
</P>
<P>
SERRA AND CARSON PLACE FOUR PLAYERS EACH ON FIRST TEAM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROB FERNAS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An appropriate theme for The Times South Bay All-Star High School Football Team 
would be "To the victors go the spoils." 
</P>
<P>
Serra, which captured its first CIF-Southern Section football title Saturday 
with a 34-31 win over Lompoc in the Division VII final, and Carson, heading 
into the L.A. City Section 4-A championship game Friday night, dominate the 
all-star squad. 
</P>
<P>
Each placed four players on the 23-member first team, which will be honored 
Sunday at The Times High School Football Awards Brunch at the Anaheim Hilton. 
Stanford Coach Dennis Green is the guest speaker. 
</P>
<P>
Winners of the South Bay Coach, Back and Lineman of the Year awards will be 
announced at the 9 a.m. brunch. 
</P>
<P>
Serra, under first-year Coach Leo Hand, put the finishing touches on a 14-0 
season with a hard-fought victory over unbeaten Lompoc at El Camino College. It 
marked only the second time in the 1980s that a South Bay football team ended 
the year with a perfect record. West Torrance was 14-0 in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
Serra is represented on the all-star team by fullback Dennis Gerard, tackle 
Kenny Thomas, linebacker Steven Johnson and safety Clayton Lopez. 
</P>
<P>
Carson (10-1) will try to win back-to-back L.A. City titles for the first time 
since 1972 at 7:30 p.m. Friday against Pacific League rival Dorsey (9-3) in the 
4-A Division final at El Camino College. The Colts have won four City 
championships in the '80s, seven overall. 
</P>
<P>
Carson players selected to the all-star first team are quarterback Armin 
Youngblood, wide receiver Michael Ross, linebacker Nkosi Littleton and 
cornerback Clayvand Thomas. 
</P>
<P>
After Serra and Carson, five schools placed two players each on the all-star 
team: Ocean League champion West Torrance, Bay League co-champions Hawthorne 
and Palos Verdes, Leuzinger and Rolling Hills. 
</P>
<P>
The Bay topped all leagues with eight selections, followed by the Pacific, 
Ocean and Camino Real with four each. 
</P>
<P>
Rounding out the offense are wide receiver Eric Hansen of North Torrance, 
linemen Robert Ferkula of South Torrance, Kyle Holderman of Palos Verdes, Jim 
Justice of Leuzinger and Corey Miller of San Pedro, running backs Chris 
Alexander of Hawthorne and Robert Coulter of Rolling Hills and kicker Angel 
Andrade of Leuzinger. 
</P>
<P>
The rest of the defensive unit is made up of linemen Jae Kim of West, Chris 
Maumalanga of Bishop Montgomery and Kenny Talanoa of El Segundo, linebackers 
Sione Mahe of Hawthorne and Jim Rudberg of Rolling Hills and defensive backs 
Mark Antrobius of Palos Verdes and Josh Moore of West. 
</P>
<P>
A closer look at the all-stars: 
</P>
<P>
WIDE RECEIVERS: 
</P>
<P>
Eric Hansen (North Torrance) -- The state's leading receiver at the end of the 
regular season, Hansen caught a South Bay-record 84 passes for 1,224 yards and 
six touchdowns in 10 games. His single-season total ranks eighth on the 
all-time Southern Section list. Said Coach Don Bohannon: "He was our offense." 
</P>
<P>
Michael Ross (Carson) -- Entering Friday's L.A. City Section 4-A title game, 
Ross has 46 catches for 862 yards (19.2 average) and 15 touchdowns. He holds 
virtually every school receiving record, eclipsing past Carson stars such as 
Wesley Walker, Michael Wilson and Derek Hill, all members of NFL teams. Ross is 
known for his sure hands, leaping ability and knack for making catches in 
traffic. 
</P>
<P>
OFFENSIVE LINEMEN: 
</P>
<P>
Robert Ferkula (South Torrance) -- Chosen the Ocean League Offensive Lineman of 
the Year, Ferkula helped pave the way for a productive running attack for the 
Ocean runners-up, who averaged nearly 200 yards rushing a game. 
</P>
<P>
Kyle Holderman (Palos Verdes) -- The top lineman and strongest player for the 
Bay League co-champions, Holderman was a standout two-way starter. "A tough, 
tough lineman," Coach Bill Judy said. "He's quick and constantly had to be 
double-teamed (on defense)." 
</P>
<P>
Jim Justice (Leuzinger) -- Rated the Olympians' No. 1 player by Coach Steve 
Carnes, the aggressive Justice anchored a line that helped Leuzinger average 
250 yards rushing a game and reach the quarterfinals of the Southern Section 
Division II playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
Kenny Thomas (Serra) -- The top lineman for the Southern Section Division VII 
champions, Thomas was a consistent performer at righttackle and helped Serra 
rush for more than 4,000 yards in 14 games. 
</P>
<P>
Corey Miller (San Pedro) -- Considered one of San Pedro's best blockers in 
recent years by Coach Henry Pacheco, Miller helped the Pirates capture the 
Southern League title with his steady play at center. 
</P>
<P>
QUARTERBACK: 
</P>
<P>
Armin Youngblood (Carson) -- A gifted athlete, Youngblood made the transition 
from running back to quarterback this season and has set several of the 
school's single-season passing records heading into Friday's championship game. 
He has completed 117 of 229 attempts (51%) for 2,306 yards and 30 touchdowns to 
lead the Colts to their ninth consecutive appearance in an L.A. City final. 
</P>
<P>
RUNNING BACKS: 
</P>
<P>
Chris Alexander (Hawthorne) -- Named the Bay League Co-Most Valuable Player, 
Alexander used his sprinter's speed (he placed fifth in the state 100 meters 
last spring) to rush for 1,133 yards on 122 carries (a 9.3 average) and score 
17 touchdowns, including a 99-yard kickoff return in the playoffs against San 
Marcos. 
</P>
<P>
Robert Coulter (Rolling Hills) -- The only junior on the first-team offense, 
Coulter led South Bay rushers during the regular season with 1,545 yards and 15 
touchdowns in 10 games. Coulter transferred from Texas late in the summer and 
quickly became the catalyst of Rolling Hills' offense with his trademark 
cut-back runs. 
</P>
<P>
Dennis Gerard (Serra) -- Chosen the Camino Real League Most Valuable Player, 
Gerard led the South Bay in rushing with 1,920 yards and 28 touchdowns in 275 
carries. The hard-running fullback saved his best for last, gaining 239 yards 
and scoring two TDs in the Division VII championship game. 
</P>
<P>
KICKER: 
</P>
<P>
Angel Andrade (Leuzinger) -- The area's second-leading kick scorer with 50 
points, Andrade converted nine of 13 field goals, including a long of 46 yards, 
and made 29 of 33 extra points. He also punted for the Olympians. 
</P>
<P>
DEFENSIVE LINEMEN: 
</P>
<P>
Jae Kim (West Torrance) -- Named the Ocean League Defensive Lineman of the 
Year, Kim was one of the South Bay's leading pass rushers. He had 11 sacks, 
including seven in the last four league games, and finished with 20 tackles for 
135 yards in losses. Kim, who also played linebacker, finished tied for the 
team lead with 58 unassisted tackles. 
</P>
<P>
Chris Maumalanga (Bishop Montgomery) -- Although the Knights were 0-4 in the 
Angelus League, the 6-4, 320-pound Maumalanga was so impressive the league's 
coaches named him Defensive Player of the Year. The two-way starter had nine 
sacks and 86 tackles. 
</P>
<P>
Kenny Talanoa (El Segundo) -- Named the Santa Fe League Lineman of the Year, 
Talanoa helped the Eagles to second place and the Southern Section Division 
VIII playoffs with his play at defensive end and tight end. 
</P>
<P>
LINEBACKERS: 
</P>
<P>
Nkosi Littleton (Carson) -- An All-L.A. City selection last season as a 
defensive lineman, Littleton blossomed into a dominating middle linebacker this 
year. He leads Carson with 131 tackles (59 unassisted), four fumble recoveries 
and two forced fumbles. He was chosen the Pacific League Defensive Player of 
the Year. 
</P>
<P>
Sione Mahe (Hawthorne) -- Selected the Bay League Defensive Player of the Year, 
Mahe's aggressive play helped the Cougars share the Bay title with Palos Verdes 
and reach the Division II playoffs. He paced Hawthorne with 161 tackles (42 
unassisted). 
</P>
<P>
Steven Johnson (Serra) -- The defensive signal caller for Serra, Johnson led 
the Cavaliers in tackles and helped the team hold opponents to an average of 
less than 10 points a game. He is known for his speed and rugged play. 
</P>
<P>
Jim Rudberg (Rolling Hills) -- A versatile two-way performer, Rudberg set the 
school record for most tackles in a season with 121 and earned the Bay League 
Offensive Player of the Year award for his blocking at tight end. 
</P>
<P>
DEFENSIVE BACKS: 
</P>
<P>
Mark Antrobius (Palos Verdes) -- The South Bay interception leader with 10, 
Antrobius rarely came off the field for the Sea Kings. He also played wide 
receiver and punted, averaging 37.6 yards a kick. He capped the season with two 
interceptions in a Division II playoff loss to Newbury Park. 
</P>
<P>
Clayton Lopez (Serra) -- Regarded as Serra's top college prospect, Lopez had 
eight interceptions and ranked second on the team in tackles. He also played 
wide receiver and contributed several big plays during the Cavaliers' drive to 
the Division VII title. 
</P>
<P>
Josh Moore (West Torrance) -- One of the area's most versatile players, Moore 
led the Warriors in interceptions (eight), rushing (750 yards in 110 carries), 
touchdowns (17) and ranked second in receptions (19 for 155 yards) playing 
running back and cornerback. He was named Ocean League Player of the Year after 
leading West to a 7-0 record and the championship. 
</P>
<P>
Clayvand Thomas (Carson) -- The only junior on the all-star defense, Thomas 
leads the Colts with six interceptions, including three he returned for 
touchdowns. The cornerback also has three deflected passes, two sacks and a 
forced fumble. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
