<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: ORANGE; 
</P>
<P>
SANTA DEBATE FINDS PROFS POLES APART 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MATT LAIT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Santa Claus works at the North Pole to avoid taxes and regulations, delivers 
his toys in the dark of night to elude Customs agents and is a master of the 
free enterprise system, a college professor jokingly asserted Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
His management style "would make the Japanese blush with envy," declared Don 
Booth, professor of economics at Chapman College during a mock college debate 
on the topic, "Santa Claus: Entrepreneurial Genius or Capitalistic Spy?" 
</P>
<P>
On the Santa-as-spy side: "Haven't you ever wondered how Santa flies around 
without setting off Russian radar?" queried Robert Slayton, a history professor 
at the college. In fact, he alleged, St. Nick's "Stealth Sled" is little more 
than a spy plane financed by the U.S. Department of Defense. 
</P>
<P>
What's more, Slayton argued, the image of Santa as a kind and gentle 
philanthropist is bunk. 
</P>
<P>
The jolly man in the red suit exploits his workers and discriminates against 
children with different religious or ethnic backgrounds, Slayton told about 60 
students who attended the debate. 
</P>
<P>
Through extensive research, Slayton said, he discovered that Santa operates a 
sweatshop type of organization, where workers toil many hours for scant wages 
and minimal benefits until they are very old with long white beards. "The 
working conditions are terrible!" he shouted. 
</P>
<P>
Slayton argued that by giving his loot to some children and not others, Santa 
discriminates against those with different beliefs and cultures. 
</P>
<P>
"Santa has corrupted Christmas, made it the symbol of class warfare," he said. 
"Moral values have been replaced by materialism and the slogan has changed from 
'Good will to all,' to 'What did you get?' " 
</P>
<P>
But Booth was unswayed by his colleague's presentation. Santa "should be 
revered as a creative, rugged individual" and a role model for business 
executives worldwide, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Santa's entrepreneurial success can be traced to his management style, Booth 
explained. "Working for Santa is such a pleasure that most people do not ask 
for any salary other than the joy they bring to others." MATT LAIT 
</P>
</TEXT>
