<P>
WATTS TRIES SAVING 'HOMEROOM' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Parents and teachers in the Watts district vowed to petition ABC to save 
"Homeroom," a half-hour comedy series they say helps keep their kids in school. 
</P>
<P>
The program, which debuted in the fall, is being canceled because of poor 
ratings, said ABC spokesman Jim Brochu. 
</P>
<P>
"All we're saying is give the show a chance," said Jim Goins, who counsels 
school dropouts in the largely minority Watts area. He and other parents and 
teachers decided to petition the network after a meeting Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
"There's not that many shows of color that deal with educational issues, and 
we're in a dilemma right now as far as having black male role models," Goins 
said. "Not everyone can be a Bill Cosby." 
</P>
<P>
"The Cosby Show," NBC's top-rated comedy, stars Bill Cosby as an upper-class 
doctor living in New York with his lawyer-wife and children. 
</P>
<P>
"Homeroom" stars Darryl Sivad as a man who gave up a lucrative job in 
advertising to teach fourth graders at an inner-city public school. 
</P>
</TEXT>
